Take-home Exercise 2

Published

December 5, 2023

Modified

December 16, 2023

1. Overview

In this take-home exercise, a case study using bus ridership in Singapore will be conducted to demonstrate the value of Geospatial Data Science and Analysis to determine factors affecting urban mobility patterns of public bus transit. To achieve this, publicly available data from different sources will be integrated to build spatial interaction models.

2. The Data

We will use the following data sets for this exercise:

S/N Name of Data Set File type Source Extracted to (file directory)
1 Master Plan 2019 Subzone Boundary (Web) SHP data.gov.sg /data/geospatial
2 HDB Property Information CSV data.gov.sg /data/aspatial
3 School Directory and Information CSV data.gov.sg /data/aspatial
4 Bus Stop Location SHP LTA DataMall /data/geospatial
5 Train Station Exit Point SHP LTA DataMall /data/geospatial
6 Passenger Volume by Origin Destination Bus Stops (202310) CSV LTA DataMall /data/aspatial
7 Businesses, retail and services, leisure and recreation SHP Assembled by Course Instructor /data/geospatial

2.1. Loading Relevant R Packages

We will first load the following packages into R using the following code:

pacman::p_load(sf, sp, tmap, stplanr,
               DT, tidyverse, reshape2,
               httr, performance, ggpubr)

These packages will serve the following purpose:

  • sf: for geospatial data handling

  • sp:

  • tmap: for thematic mapping

  • stplanr: for transport planning using spatial transport data

  • DT: for data frames interface

  • tidyverse: for non-spatial data handling

  • reshape2:

  • httr: for working with URLs and HTTP

  • performance: to compute model comparison matrices

  • ggpubr: for creating statistical graphics

2.3. Extract Study Data

For this exercise, we will explore the commuter flow on weekday afternoon peak periods. Besides returning home at the end of the workday, commuters could travel out from their workplace in search of food, entertainment or retail experiences.

od_WD_PM <- odbus %>%
  filter(DAY_TYPE == 'WEEKDAY') %>%
  filter(TIME_PER_HOUR >= 17 &
          TIME_PER_HOUR <= 20) %>%
  group_by(ORIGIN_PT_CODE, DESTINATION_PT_CODE) %>%
  summarise(TRIPS = sum(TOTAL_TRIPS))

3. Create Hexagon Layer

Next, we will create a hexagon tessellation layer using mpsz2019. A hexagon layer is created to replace the irregular planning subzone polygons to reduce sampling bias. We will use the following code to generate the hexagon layer based on a perpendicular disctance from center to edge of hexagon of 375m.

# cell size = 2 x edge length (regular hexagons are made of equilateral triangles)
# apothem = perpendicular distance from center to any edge
# edge length = (2 x apothem) / sqrt(3) 
# cell size = (4 x apothem) / sqrt(3)
cs <- (4 * 375) / sqrt(3)

# make hexagonal tesellation and add grid ID
mpsz2019_grid <- st_make_grid(mpsz2019, c(cs,cs), square = FALSE) %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  mutate(id = row_number())

mpsz2019_grid$id <- as.factor(mpsz2019_grid$id)

# determine centroid for each hexagon
cent <- st_centroid(mpsz2019_grid)

# determine the intersection of centroids with mpsz2019
mpsz2019_map <- st_intersection(cent, mpsz2019)

cent_no_geom <- st_drop_geometry(mpsz2019_map)

# create hexagon layer, drop_na() to suppress cells outside the country
hexagon <- left_join(mpsz2019_grid, cent_no_geom) %>%
  drop_na()

qtm(hexagon)

4. Origin-Destination Flow

4.1. Create Origin-Destination Matrix

We will use the following code to populate the hexagon grid id from the hexagon layer sf dataframe to busstop sf dataframe:

bs_hexagon <- st_intersection(busstop, hexagon) %>%
  select(BUS_STOP_N, id) %>%
  st_drop_geometry()

datatable(bs_hexagon)

st_intersection() is used to perform point and polygon overlay, output is in point sf object. Five bus stops are dropped from the results as they are outside Singapore’s boundaries.

Next, we will append the hexagon grid id from bs_hexagon onto the od_WD_PM dataframe:

od_data <- left_join(od_WD_PM, bs_hexagon,
                     by = c("ORIGIN_PT_CODE" = "BUS_STOP_N")) %>%
  rename(ORIGIN_BS = ORIGIN_PT_CODE,
         #ORIGIN_SZ = SUBZONE_C,
         DESTIN_BS = DESTINATION_PT_CODE)

5. Prepare Inter-zone Flow Data for Modelling

5.1. Compute Distance Matrix

Computing distance matrix using sf method takes relatively longer than using sp method. Hence, sp method is used in the codes below.

First, we will convert the hexagon layer from sf tibble data frame to SpatialPolygonsDataFrame:

hexagon_sp <- as(hexagon, "Spatial")

grid_id <- hexagon$id

Next, we will pivot the distance matrix into a long table by using row and column subzone codes:

dist_matrix <- melt(dist) %>%
  rename(dist = value)

It is observed that intra-zonal distance is 0.

As we will be using log on distance in the Spatial Interaction Model, we have to replace the 0 values with a constant value.

First, we will determine the minimum of the distance:

dist_matrix %>%
  filter(dist > 0) %>%
  summary()
      Var1           Var2           dist      
 Min.   :  53   Min.   :  53   Min.   :  866  
 1st Qu.: 785   1st Qu.: 785   1st Qu.: 9987

 Mean   :1367   Mean   :1367   Mean   :17798  
 3rd Qu.:1860   3rd Qu.:1860   3rd Qu.:23922  
 Max.   :3019   Max.   :3019   Max.   :56980

Next, we will add a constant value of 866m into intra-zonal distance:

dist_matrix$dist <- ifelse(dist_matrix$dist == 0, 866,
                         dist_matrix$dist) 

summary(dist_matrix)
      Var1           Var2           dist      
 Min.   :  53   Min.   :  53   Min.   :  866

Next, we will rename

dist_matrix <- dist_matrix %>%
  rename(origin = Var1,
         destin = Var2)

dist_matrix$origin <- as.factor(dist_matrix$origin)
dist_matrix$destin <- as.factor(dist_matrix$destin)

Lastly, we will add distance to the inter_zone data.frame.

interzone_data <- flow_line %>%

5.2. Preparing Propulsive and Attractiveness Attributes

First, we identify the following propulsive and attractiveness attributes as factors affecting commute flows on weekend PM peak period:

Propulsive: 1. Business: as the origin of the PM peak travels where people leave their workplaces 2. Financial centres: as the origin of the PM peak travels where people leave their workplaces 3. Schools: as the origin of the PM peak travels where students leave their schools after completing school activities

Attractiveness: 1. F&B: as the destination of PM peak travels where people look for dinner options 2. Leisure and recreation: as the destination of PM peak travels where people seek to relax after a day of work 3. HDB: as the destination of PM peak travels where people return home after work or school

5.2.2. Geocode HDB Information

We will repeat the above steps to geocode the hdb_2023 CSV file, which contains the property information of HDB blocks in Singapore as of October 2023. As the HDB property information does not contain postal codes, we will geocode using the SLA API with the address of each HDB block.

url <- "https://www.onemap.gov.sg/api/common/elastic/search"

csv <- read_csv("data/aspatial/hdb_2023.csv")
# create a list of all postal codes from schools.csv
address <- paste(csv$"blk_no", csv$"street")

found <- data.frame()
not_found <- data.frame()

# pass list of postal code for geocoding
for(add in address){
  query <- list('searchVal' = add, 'returnGeom' = 'Y', 
                'getAddrDetails' = 'Y','pageNum' = '1')
  res <- GET(url, query = query)
  
  if((content(res)$found)!=0){
    found <- rbind(found, data.frame(content(res))[4:13])
  } else{
    not_found = data.frame(add)
  }
}

glimpse(found)
glimpse(not_found)

It is observed that one postal code was not geocoded through the API. We will first export the results as CSV in order to merge the original hdb_2023 and results files.

write.csv(found, file = "data/aspatial/hdb_2023_found.csv")

Now, we will import the updated schools_geocoded CSV file into the R environment:

hdb <- read_csv("data/aspatial/hdb_2023_geocoded.csv") %>%
  rename(latitude = results.LATITUDE,
         longitude = results.LONGITUDE,
         postal_code = results.POSTAL) %>%
  # keep only relevant columns in R
  filter(residential == "Y", commercial == "N") %>%

We will use total_dwelling_units as a proxy of the number of residents living in that housing block, which will later be aggregated at the hexagon level. First, based on data from the Department of Statistcis, the average household size among resident households is 3.09. We will use this to estimate the number of people living in each block:

https://tablebuilder.singstat.gov.sg/table/TS/M810371

hdb$residents <- round((hdb$total_dwelling_units * 3.09),0)

6. Spatial Interaction Models

We will use flow_data to fit into the following four modelling techniques using the Poisson Regression method. Thereafter, we will determine the most suitable model.

  1. Unconstrained
  2. Production-constrained
  3. Attraction-constrained
  4. Doubly-constrained

6.1. R-squared Function

We will write a function to calculate R-squared value to measure how much variation of the trips can be accounted by each model:

calc_Rsquared <- function(observed, estimated){
  r <- cor(observed, estimated)
  R2 <- r^2
  R2
}

6.2. Unconstrained Spatial Interaction Model

In this section, we will calibrate an unconstrained spatial interaction model using the glm() function from Base Stats. The explanatory variables are origin population by different age cohort, destination population by different age cohort and distance between origin and destination in km.

We will use the following code to calibrate the model:

uncSIM <- glm(formula = TRIPS ~
                log(ORI_BUSINESS) +
                log(ORI_FINANCE) +
                log(ORI_TRAIN) +
                log(DES_FOOD) +
                log(DES_LEISURE) +
                log(DES_HOME) +
                log(dist),
              family = poisson(link = "log"),
              data = SIM_data,
              na.action = na.exclude)
summary(uncSIM)

6.3. Origin Constrained SIM

We will fit an origin constrained SIM by using the following code:

orcSIM <- glm(formula = TRIPS ~
                origin_id +
                log(DES_FOOD) +
                log(DES_LEISURE) +
                log(DES_HOME) +
                log(dist) - 1,
              family = poisson(link = "log"),
              data = SIM_data,
              na.action = na.exclude)

summary(orcSIM)

6.4. Destination Constrained

In this section, we will fit a destination constrained SIM by using the following code:

decSIM <- glm(formula = TRIPS ~
                destin_id +
                log(ORI_BUSINESS) +
                log(ORI_FINANCE) +
                #log(ORI_SCHOOL) +
                log(ORI_TRAIN) +
                log(dist) -1 ,
              family = poisson(link = "log"),
              data = SIM_data,
              na.action = na.exclude)

summary(decSIM)

                destin_id +

              data = SIM_data,
              na.action = na.exclude)

6.6. Model Comparison

Another useful model performance measure of continuous dependent variable is Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE). We will use the compare_performance() function from the performance package.

Firstly, we will create a list called model_list by using the following code:

model_list <- list(unconstrained = uncSIM,
                   originConstrained = orcSIM,
                   destinConstrained = decSIM,
                   doublyConstrained = dbcSIM)

Next, we will compute the RMSE of all models in the model_list:

compare_performance(model_list,
                    metrics = "RMSE")
# Comparison of Model Performance Indices

Name              | Model |     RMSE
------------------------------------
unconstrained     |   glm | 1668.600
originConstrained |   glm | 1429.167
destinConstrained |   glm | 1521.038
doublyConstrained |   glm | 1170.515

6.7. Visuslising Fitted

We will visualise the observed and fitted values. First, we will extract the fitted values from each model using the following code:

df <- as.data.frame(uncSIM$fitted.values) %>%
  round(digits = 0)

Next, we will join the values to SIM_data dataframe:

SIM_data <- SIM_data %>%
  cbind(df) %>%
  rename(uncTRIPS = "uncSIM.fitted.values")

We will repeat the same steps for:

Origin Constrained SIM

df <- as.data.frame(orcSIM$fitted.values) %>%
  round(digits = 0)
SIM_data <- SIM_data %>%
  cbind(df) %>%
  rename(orcTRIPS = "orcSIM.fitted.values")

Destination Constrained SIM

df <- as.data.frame(decSIM$fitted.values) %>%
  round(digits = 0)

  cbind(df) %>%
  rename(decTRIPS = "decSIM.fitted.values")

Doubly Constrained SIM

df <- as.data.frame(dbcSIM$fitted.values) %>%
  round(digits = 0)

  cbind(df) %>%
  rename(dbcTRIPS = "dbcSIM.fitted.values")

                aes(x = uncTRIPS,
